  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements aimed at combating money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Global standards for preventing money laundering\n- 40 recommendations that countries are encouraged to implement\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention against Corruption\n\n3. Basel Committee Principles\n- Guidelines for banking supervision and anti-money laundering practices\n\n4. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Establish regulations for financial institutions in EU member states\n\n5. International Monetary Fund (IMF) Guidelines\n- Provide framework for countries to develop anti-money laundering policies\n\nThese laws typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement internal compliance programs\n\nWhile these are international standards, individual countries implement and enforce their own specific laws based on these guidelines.\n\nMost developed countries have robust anti-money laundering laws and actively work to prevent financial crimes.",
